(10, 'stud2', 5, 'stud2_7_1765908043538_task_5_1765906753.pdf', '2025-12-17 02:00:43', '2025-12-17 02:00:43', 7, '', NULL),
(11, 'stud2', 5, 'stud2_7_1765908072982_1_stud2_chap3_psm.pdf', '2025-12-17 02:01:12', '2025-12-17 02:01:12', 7, ' \n    \n              \n        \n    \n    \n \nA Plagiarism Detector in Learning Management  \nSystem  for UTHM  \n       \n       \n       \n       \n       \nNAMA       \nName       :   DIV AKHAR A/L RAJAH       \nNO. MATRIK      \nMatric No.       :   AI230082      \nTARIKH       \nDate       :   4/12/2025       \nSUPERVISOR       :   Dr. Nur Ziadah Binti Harun       \n     \n                                                          \n    \n   \n \n    \n \n CHAP TER THREE  \nMETHODOLOGY  \nThis chapter explain the use of prototype model in this project and the activities that \nhad been carried out in each phase.  \n3.1 Agile Model  \nThe Agile Model is an iterative development process that creates prototype system \nversions that can be further enhanced through multiple iterations . Continuous delivery \nof user feedback helps to implement ongoing improvements to each new version of \nthe prototype. The Agile approach emphasizes user satisfaction, collaborative \nprocesses, and flexibility in producing a final product that continues to impr ove over \ntime by using the multiple refinements from iterations throughout the entire life cycle \nof the product. The Agile Model contains the following phases , Analysis , Design , \nDevelopment , Testing , Deployment , Feedback , and the Iteration . Each phase is \ndeveloped from the last, and iterations are utilized between phases to allow for \ncontinuous sharing between phases until the prototypes develop into the final system.  \n3.1.1 Planning Phase  \nDuring the planning phase of the project, the information w as gathered on the project \ngoals, objectives, and requirements through discussions with stakeholders including , \nlecturers , students,  and UTHM IT portal team. The planning phase defines the \nrequirements for the plagiarism detection modul e. For example , the ability to upload \ndocuments, check for similarities, manage users, and create reports. The project scope, \nproject constraints, timeline and technologies required for the project are also \nestablished. The planning phase creates user stories or feature lists to represent what \nthe system will be like from a user\'s perspective. User  stories and lists will form the \nbasis of future development cycles. The planning phase will help ensure that the \ndevelopment process is  understand able on  what will need to be developed prior to \nmoving on.  \n \n \n   \n3.1.2 Analysis Phase  \nTo successfully design and develop a plagiarism detection  in a Learning Management \nSystem , it is important to first conduct an analysis phase of each functional and \ntechnical requirement. The Analysis phase is necessary to determine the functional and \ntechnical requirements for a plagiarism detection module, and to prepare the system to \nmeet t he specific needs of its users, including students and lecturers. The analysis \nphase identifies student needs, including the ability for students to upload assignments \nwith ease and receive notifications when their assignment has been submitted. Lecturer \nneeds include automated similarity verification, detailed similarity rep orts, and ease of \naccess to student documents. The analysis phase also determines the types of \nalgorithms that will be used to process, compare, and validate submitted documents \nand defines how submitted documents will be processed, stored, and compared.  \nAnalysis of current challenges experienced by AUTHOR, including the lack of \nan integrated plagiarism detection system, will be performed to ensure that the new \nsystem addresses these challenges and includes all the pertinent requirements. This \nanalysis pha se will also examine all of the technical limitations associated with \nimplementing a plagiarism detection module, including  accuracy of algorithms, server \nloads, and response time requirements, to ensure that the completed system meets all \nof these technical requirements. Upon conclusion of this analysis phase, a detailed \nsystem requirements list and workflow behaviour for the  proposed plagiarism \ndetection system will be published to assist with the subsequent design and \ndevelopment of the plagiarism detection module.  \n3.1.3 Design Phase  \nWhen creating the system design, all aspects of the system were organized so that it \ncould function properly and be easy for both instructors and students to use. To do this, \nit was necessary to define the main components of the system, how the plagiarism \ndetection module interacts with the submission process, and how the layout of the user \ninterface will make it feel easy to navigate. It was also necessary to identify how the \nsystem handles certain functions, including file uploads, generating similarity r eports, \nand providing alerts  or notifications to users.  Using Entity -Relationship Diagrams \n(ERD)  and Data Flow Diagram (DFD) , the database structure is designed  continuously.  The design creates a comprehensive and organized plan  to reference and \nensure the system meets user needs.  \n \n \n3.1.4 Im plementation Phase  \nThe development of the system occurs in phases using an Agile Approach. A series of \nsprints will break down each function into smaller chunks. The main functions of the \nsystem that will be developed incrementally are  User Login, Document Upload, \nSimilarity Comparison, and Report Creation. Each chunk of development will be built, \ntested, and refined during a sprint until the final function is ready for production. In \naddition to these features, the algorithms used for detecting plagiarism will be created \nand integrated into the submission workflow for automatic analysis of any document \nuploaded.  \nProgramming for backend functionality is done within the PHP and Python \nenvironment and database functionality is completed using MySQL. The frontend \nfunctionality is developed with HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. As each module is \ncompleted, stakeholders will have the opportunity to view how it works and provide \ninput. If there are any recommended changes, they will be made before moving \nforward with the next sprint.  \n3.1.5 Testing Phase  \nThe testing process is designed to verify that the System performs in accordance with \nthe requirements specified and that it works correctly and efficiently. The first stage of \ntesting is Unit Testing. During this stage each Module (e.g., File Uploading, S imilarity \nCheck Calculation, Report Generation) is tested separately to verify it is functioning \nas expected. The next stage of testing is System Integration Testing. During System \nIntegration Testing, modules are tested together as a complete system and the flow of \ndata between Modules is verified as being error -free. The final stage of testing is User \nAcceptance Testing (UAT). During UAT, Lecturers and Students test the system to \nassure themselves that it is easy to use, performs as intended, and satisfies th e needs \nof its users. Each of the above tests contributes to creating a reliable, usable, and \nDeployable System.   3.2 Syste m Develop ment Workflow  \nThere are a total of seven  phases from the prototype model. As shown in Table 3.1, \neach phase has its assignment and output that needs to be produced during the entire \nproject development. Besides that, the output had been completed within the specific \ndays that were given.  \n \nTable 3.1 : Software development activities and their task  \nPhase  Tasks  Outputs  \nPlanning  • Define project objectives and \nscope  \n• Identify users (lecturer & \nstudent)  \n• Determine features and \nconstraints  \n• Develop project timeline and \nresource plan  • Project scope definition  \n• Preliminary timeline  \n \nAnalysis  • Gather system requirements \nfrom lecturer and students  \n• Identify functional and non -\nfunctional requirements  \n• Prepare use -case descriptions \nand workflow scenarios  • Software Requirements \nSpecification (SRS)  \n• List of system \nrequirements  \n• Develop Gantt chart   \n \nDesign  • Develop system architecture \nand workflow  \n• Design user interface layout \nand mockups  • UI mockups/layouts  \n• System architecture \ndesign  \n• Database schema and \nDFD   • Plan database schema and data \nrelationships  • Entity Relationship \nDiagram  \nImplementation  • Develop UI using chosen \ntechnology  \n• Code system modules \n(submission, evaluation, \nfeedback, etc.)  \n• Integrate front -end and \ndatabase  \n• Conduct internal debugging  • Working prototype  \n•Functional module \nintegration  \n• Source code files  \nTesting  • Conduct functional testing of \neach feature  \n• Perform user acceptance \ntesting with lecturer and \nstudents  \n• Identify and log bugs/issues  • Test case results  \n• UAT feedback forms  \n• List of bugs and \nimprovement items  \nFeedback & \nIteration  • Collect detailed feedback from \nlecturers and students  \n• Review issues, usability \nconcerns, missing requirements  \n• Refine and update prototype \nbased on findings  \n• Retest after modifications  • Improvement summary  \n• Updated prototype \nversion  \n• Validation report after \niteration  \n \n \n \n  3.3 Chapter Summary  \nThe methodology used to design the prototype plagiarism detection system for UTHM  \nis detailed in this chapter . This chapter introduces the iterative approach selected \nbecause it enables ongoing improvements based on input from both instructors and \nstudents. Each phase of development is outlined, beginning with the planning phase \nwhere objectives and scope are est ablished, then moving on to analysing the functional \nrequirements and user requirements. The design phase provides an overview of the \nsystem architecture, interface design, and database schema that were all converted into \na live prototype during implementa tion. Once the prototype was developed, testing \nwas performed to ensure functionality and usability of the system and any problems \nfound were addressed through the structured test and review cycle outlined in the \nmethodology. This methodology allowed for t he creation of a practical and user -\nfriendly system that effectively meets the goals of Academic Integrity.  ', NULL);
