(21, 'stud1', 5, 'stud1_11_1776707344213_psm_chap1final.pdf', '2026-04-21 01:49:04', '2026-04-21 01:49:04', 11, ' \n  \n   \n    \n              \n                     \n    \n    \n       \nA Plagiarism Detector in Learning Management System for \nUTHM    \n       \n       \n       \n       \n       \nNAMA       \nName       :   DIV AKHAR A/L RAJAH       \nNO. MATRIK      \nMatric No.       :   AI230082      \nTARIKH       \nDate       :   8/11/2025       \nSUPERVISOR       :   Dr. Nur Ziadah Binti Harun       \n     \n                                                          \n    \n   \n    \n    \n    \n    \n    \n 2       \n       \n    \nCHAPTER ONE    \n    \nINTRODUCTION    \n    \n    \n    \n      \n1.1 Project Background       \n    \nA Plagiarism Detector in Learning Management System (LMS) for UTHM, is to provide \nan integrated plagiarism detection tool for the learning management system that lecturers \nand students at Universiti Tun Hussein Onn Malaysia (UTHM) utilise. The goal is to help \nlecturers check student assignments\' originality withi n the LMS system without relying on \nexternal technologies. The technology automatically compares the content of an \nassignment uploaded by a student to other submissions that have been stored, generating \na comprehensive similarity report for lecturers. The initiative improves academic integrity \nand expedites the assignment review process by integrating this feature into the LMS.    \nAccoring to Sozon et al . (2024) , cheating and plagiarism have become serious \nproblems in higher education institutions (HEIs). It affects educational quality as well as \nthe reputation of higher education. In order to guarantee that students produce original \nwork, plagiarism detection is a crucial part of contemporary academic institutions. \nLecturers have historically relied on outside plagiarism detection software, which \nnecessitates manual uploads, different logins, and occasionally extra fees. By incorporating \nplagiarism detection into th e LMS, lecturers and students may have a more seamless \nexperience while maintaining the security of all data in the university\'s digital environment.   \nAdditional features like blockchain function, encrypted storage, secure \nauthentication, and an analytical reporting module are included in the architecture of the \nsuggested system. According to Wang  et al. ( 2025) , within the education sphere, \nblockchain applications protect academic records, ensure their trustworthiness, reduce \nfraud, and improve the value of educational assets. Every student’s submission, plagiarism \nreport, and grading record can be stored as a tr ansaction on the blockchain. Once data is \nadded, it cannot be altered or deleted without leaving a trace. This ensures that lecturers \nand students cannot modify submission dates or plagiarism scores dishonestly.   \nAdditionally, the system\'s architecture promotes accountability and openness by \nenabling lecturers to quickly examine plagiarism reports and make knowledgeable \nassessments.    3       \n       \n       \n      \n     \nUltimately, this project adds value through automation, data consistency, and user \nease, which helps to improve the current LMS, AUTHOR. It offers a safe, effective, and \nuser-friendly plagiarism detection tool while supporting UTHM\'s dedication to promotin g \nacademic achievement and innovation in digital learning environments.    \n \n1.2    Problem Statement       \n       \nAccording to  Turn bull et al. (2022), l earning management systems form an integral \npart of the learning environments of most universities and support a wide range of \ndiverse activities and operations. Nevertheless, despite their significance, there are still \na number of issues that have an impa ct on academic institutions\' efficiency, data \nintegrity, and performance monitoring. These difficulties underscore the need for an \nenhanced system that guarantees confidentiality, transparency, and authenticity in \nacademic contributions while also facilita ting learning.    \nUniversities like UTHM must implement cutting -edge resources that meet the \ndemands of contemporary teaching and learning as higher education moves towards \nincreasingly digital and automated processes. The institution\'s capacity to guarantee \noriginality, data security, and efficiency is hampered by the  existing LMS\'s lack of an \nintegrated plagiarism detection capability. In addition to enhancing academic reputation,  \nthe implementation of an integrated plagiarism detector will show UTHM\'s dedication to  \ndeveloping educational technology. According to Hijriyanti et al. (2020),  with the \ndevelopment of technology in education, of course, innovation in learning develops for the \nbetter.  \nThe absence of crucial security features like activity tracking, and encrypted data \nstorage is another major worry. Sensitive academic data, including as assignments, grades, \nand user credentials, is nonetheless susceptible to illegal access and data breac hes in the \nabsence of these. According to Almusfar  et al. (2025) , data security stands out as crucial \nbecause any weaknesses can result in breaches that erode user confidence. Through \ntransparent, impenetrable record management, strengthening the LMS with improved \nsecurity layers and blockchain hash integration can prot ect data and uphold academic \nintegrity by detecting duplicates or tampered content.    4       \n       \nFurthermore, the majority of LMS platforms currently in use have user interfaces \nthat are frequently complicated or difficult to use, as well as restricted analytics \ncapabilities. This makes it challenging for lecturers to adequately detect trends of acade mic \ndishonesty, identify learning gaps, and measure student progress. By using real -time \nanalytics tools, lecturers can get useful information about student performance, interest \nlevels, and plagiarism patterns, encouraging proactive academic support.      \nTo sum up, these difficulties show how important it is to create a more sophisticated \nand safe LMS for UTHM. The goal of the suggested plagiarism detection system is to \ndevelop a dependable, open, and effective academic platform that upholds the highest \nstandards of academic integrity while improving teaching and learning opportunities.    \n      \n1.3    Objective       \n       \nThe objectives of this system are to:       \n      \n1. Develop a Secure Learning Management System that includes an AutoPlagiarism \nDetection function to improve academic integrity.      \n      \n2. Propose an enhanced platform with cutting -edge features designed specifically for \nUTHM lecturers and students, including performance metrics, real -time \nnotifications, and transparent plagiarism reporting.      \n      \n3. Test the system\'s efficacy, dependability, and usability through functional testing \nand user acceptance tests.      \n            \n               \n1.4   Scope       \n       \nThe design and development of a plagiarism detection tool within a Learning Management   \nSystem (LMS) specifically for Universiti Tun Hussein Onn Malaysia (UTHM) is the main \nobjective of this project. The system\'s goal is to offer a comprehensive, safe, and effective \nplatform for handling academic assignments and guaranteeing student inputs ar e unique. \nStudents can upload their assignments straight through the LMS, and lecturers can check  \nthe similarity report that is produced by the integrated plagiarism detection system. By \nremoving the need for external plagiarism tools and guaranteeing that  all operations are \nconfined within a single, cohesive platform, this procedure helps optimise academic \nworkflows.   \nThe system scope includes data encryption to safeguard academic files, and user \nauthentication for safe access in addition to plagiarism detection. Lecturers will have  5       \n       \n       \n      \n     \naccess to alternatives for effectively managing assignments, comprehensive plagiarism \nreports, and data on student submissions. In the meantime, students can track deadlines  \nwith automated notifications, view submission statuses, and get feedback on their  \noriginality. According to  Lo et al. (20 12), a daptive web -based system can help the student \nobtain information in a form that fits the students’ characteristics and fulfills the user’s real \nneeds automatically over the web. Web -based technologies including PHP, MySQL, \nHTML, CSS, and JavaScript will be  used in the system\'s development to provide \naccessibility across a variety of devices and browsers. The project\'s overall scope includes \ndeveloping, testing, and implementing a user -friendly, safe, and efficient LMS feature that \nenhances UTHM\'s digital le arning environment and supports academic integrity.    \n      \nTable 1: Users of System   \nUser Type             Responsibilities       \n  \n   Lecturer       •  Set the sensitivity of plagiarism detection for each \nassignment or course.      \n     \n       •  Get class -wide data and automated plagiarism   \nreports.     \n      •  Track metrics related to student behaviour, such as \ninactivity, late submissions, and recurring high similarity \nscores.      \n      •  Upload teaching materials safely using watermarks or  \ndownload limits.                       \n      •  Offer ideas for assignment or quiz grading.      \n •  \n      Get notifications about possible problems with academic \nintegrity, such as the detection of plagiarised content.      \nStudent   •  Get pop -up alerts about impending deadlines for \nassignments.       6       \n       \n •  Send in assignments over an encrypted, safe upload \nchannel.      \n •  Receive immediate comments or report on plagiarism and \nrecommendations for appropriate citations.   \n •   Keep track of each submission\'s own plagiarism history.      \n •  \n   Get learning insights and study reminders.    \n  \n  \nTable 2: Functional Modules   \nMODULE       FUNCTION       \nUser   Authentication    \nModule        Ensures safe access for administrators, lecturers, and \nstudents via role -based access control, two -factor \nauthentication, and login credentials.      \n      \nCourse       \nManagement Module     Enables creation, editing, and organization of courses, \nassignments, lecture materials, and announcements.      \nAssignment      \nSubmission &      \nPlagiarism Module      Records submission history, offers real -time originality \nreports, automatically checks for plagiarism, and enables \nstudents to turn in work safely.      \n      \nNotification &      \nReminder Module      Sends emails and pop -up notifications in real time about \nimpending deadlines for assignments, plagiarism alerts, and \ncourse announcements.      \n      \nPerformance Analytics    \nModule       Creates class -level statistics, plagiarism trends, submission \npatterns, and student performance dashboards to help \nlecturers make data -driven decisions.      \nCommunication &      \nCollaboration Module     Enables safe assignment feedback, discussion boards, and  \nmessaging between students and lecturers.    7       \n       \n       \n      \n     \n      \nData Backup &      \nSecurity Module      To avoid data loss or unwanted access, it makes sure that all \nsystem data, submissions, and reports are secured, safely \nstored, and routinely backed up.      \n      \n              \n1.5      Expected Outcome       \n       \nA fully working Learning Management System with an integrated plagiarism detection \nfeature that improves academic integrity and expedites assignment grading at UTHM is \nthe anticipated result of this project. In order to facilitate equitable and effective g rading, \nthe system is supposed to automatically assess submitted projects for originality, produce \nprecise similarity reports, and give lecturers comprehensive insights. Additionally, it will \nensure that sensitive academic materials are shielded from unwan ted access by \nstrengthening data security through user authentication and encryption. The system \nattempts to lessen the effort of lecturers, improve feedback turnaround time and give \nstudents a more transparent and effective submission process by combining  assignment \nmanagement and plagiarism detection into a single platform. In the end, the initiative will \nhelp UTHM create a digital learning environment that is more safe, datadriven, and \nintegrity -focused.    \n  \n1.6      Project Significant       \n       \nThis project is important because it can improve academic integrity, security, and \nefficiency in the digital learning environment at UTHM. The initiative reduces expenses, \nprotects data privacy, and streamlines the workflow for lecturers and students by \nintegrating a plagiarism detection mechanism directly into the Learning Management \nSystem. This system encourages integrity and creativity in academic submissions while \nalso streamlining assignment review. By adding secure authentication, automatic checks, \nand analytical tools to facilitate well -informed decision -making, it also fortifies the \norganization\'s digital infrastructure. All things considered, the project helps create a more  8       \n       \ndependable, secure, and user -friendly academic platform that meets the changing demands \nof higher education.  \n \n1.7 Chapter Organization     \n \nThis report contains six chapters as follows:     \n \nChapter 1 describes the introduction of the project background, problem statement, \nobjective, scope, expected result, methodology, project planning and project significant.     \nChapter 2 reviewed all the relevant theoretical literature used in the proposed system.     \nChapter 3 describes the relevant methodology for the proposed system.     \nChapter 4 explains the analysis and design of the development system.     \nChapter 5 explains the implementation and testing of the development system.     \nChapter 6 describes the conclusion and future work for the proposed system.    \n  \n1.8 References    \n   \nSozon M, Mohammad Alkharabsheh OH, Fong PW, Chuan SB. Cheating and plagiarism  \nin higher education institutions (HEIs): A  literature review. F1000Res. 2024 Sep \n26;13:788. doi: 10.12688/f1000research.147140.2. PMID: 39429635; PMCID:  \n         PMC11489843.   \n \nX. Wang, M. Younas, Y . Jiang, M. Imran and N. Almusharraf, \"Transforming Education \nThrough  Blockchain: A Systematic Review of Applications, Projects, and Challenges,\"   \nin IEEE Access, vol. 13, pp. 13264 -13284, 2025, doi: 10.1109/ACCESS.2024.3519350.  \n  \nTurnbull D, Chugh R, Luck J. An Overview of the Common Elements of Learning \nManagement System Policies in Higher Education Institutions. TechTrends. \n2022;66(5):855 -867. doi: 10.1007/s11528 -022-00752 -7. Epub 2022 Jul 5. PMID:  \n     35813034; PMCID: PMC9255472.   \n  \nElmabaredy, A., Elkholy, E. & Tolba, AA. Web -based adaptive presentation techniques to \nenhance learning outcomes in higher education.  RPTEL  15, 20 (2020). \nhttps://doi.org/10.1186/s41039 -020-00140 -w  \n   9       \n       \n       \n      \n     \nL. A. Almusfar, \"Improving Learning Management System Performance: A \nComprehensive Approach to Engagement, Trust, and Adaptive Learning,\" in IEEE \nAccess, vol. 13, pp. 46408 -46425, 2025, doi: 10.1109/ACCESS.2025.3550288.   \n  \nHijriyanti, Aulia & Cholifah, Maria & Purnawati, Maria. (2020). JURNAL ILMIAH \nBAHASA DAN SASTRA THE ANALYSIS OF STUDENTS\' PERCEPTION ON THE \nUSE OF E -LEARNING AS AN EDUCATIONAL METHOD. Jurnal Ilmiah Bahasa dan  \n     Sastra. 7. 54 -62.  \n  ', 8.20),
(22, 'stud2', 5, 'stud2_11_1776707396506_chap2_psmfinal.pdf', '2026-04-21 01:49:56', '2026-04-21 01:49:56', 11, ' \n   \n    \n              \n        \n    \n    \n       \n       A Plagiarism Detector in Learning Management System     \nfor UTHM  \n       \n       \n       \n       \n       \nNAMA       \nName       :   DIVAKHAR A/L RAJAH       \nNO. MATRIK      \nMatric No.       :   AI230082      \nTARIKH       \nDate       :   30/11/2025       \nSUPERVISOR       :   Dr. Nur Ziadah Binti Harun       \n     \n                                                          \n    \n   \n    \n CHAPTER TWO  \n \nLITERATURE REVIEW  \n \n2.1 Introduction  \nThe chapter provides a comparison of Learning Management Systems (LMS) that are \nsignificant to this research in terms of technology, features, and shortfalls. An LMS is simply \na means of providing educational materials, assigning and submitting homework, a nd \ncommunicating between students and lecturers . The way they approach automation, data safe -\nhandling, plagiarism detection, and learning analytics varies widely among different systems. \nThe main LMS used by UTHM is Author [1], which supports academic activities at UTHM \nbut has limited features for managing the submission of assignments.  \nThe analysis of the comparison with other systems identifies where gaps exist to build \nan integrated plagiarism detection solution tailored specifically for the LMS of UTHM. From \nthis comparison, the identified information will be used to create a more sec ure, efficient, and \nsupportive LMS for academic success.  \n \n2.2 Manual  or Traditional Study Assessment  \nManual or Traditional  Study Assessments consist of lecturers  taking print -offs out of the mail, \ngoing through them individually, writing in their own comments for each student\'s papers, and \nkeeping track of students\' grades in a hard -copy format. This process causes lecturers  to \nphysically handle and store large numbers of printed papers, which is time -consuming and \ntedious. Lecturers  have difficulty identifying similarities and evidence of plagiarism or \ncopying, because they have to rely solely on their memories and their observations; this adds \ninconsistency and l owers the level of trust in the assessment process. Identifying student \nsuccess and failure and providing timely feedback becomes difficult when there are no \nelectronic systems to assist lecturers . Electronic assessment systems would address these \nconstraints by reducing the amount of time needed to assess and grade various forms of student \nassessments; eliminate the possibility of misplaced assessment materials; provide more ways \nfor lecturers  to communicate feedback to their students; and reduce the amoun t of effort \nrequired to create, manage, and maintain assessment material for each individual student [2].   \n2.3 Learning Management System  \nLearning Management System is a computer -based system to manage, facilitate, \nmonitor, and evaluate training activities  [3]. It provides an online learning environment that \ngathers all of the content associated with the teaching and learning process into one location \nfor use by all stakeholders ( lecturers , students) involved in the process. Lecturers  may upload \ntheir training materials to the LMS, assign assignments, administer assessments, publish \ntraining information or updates, and monitor how engaged students are with their assigned \nmaterials. Students can access any of their assigned training mat erials at any time, submit \ncompleted assignments, communicate with their lecturer  about any questions that they may \nhave about the content, and track their academic progress through the LMS.  \nThere are many advantages of using a learning management system in today\'s education \nsystem [4]. The most noteworthy is the flexibility that it provides for students because they can \nlearn at their own pace and access the materials from anywhere in the world. This flexibility \nallows for students to participate in learning activities in a way that acco mmodates their \nindividual learning styles and schedules. Additionally, LMS systems can be used to automate \nadministrative tasks, such as grading, tracking attendance, and distributing course content. \nLMS also facilitates the communication between lecture rs and students by including automated \nmessaging functions, forums, and notifications.  Furthermore, LMS systems maintain digital \nrecords of submissions, grades, and feedback, promoting transparency and reducing the risk of \nmisplaced documents. Overall, an LMS improves teaching effectiveness, strengthens student \nengagement, and provides a sca lable and sustainable approach to digital learning.  \n \n2.4 Plagiarism  \nPlagiarism is seen as the act of using someone else’s ideas, methods, or other written works \nwithout having received prior approval from the original author, and with the intention to have \nthe work credited to you. There are many reasons why people commit this offense and many \ndifferent factors that lead someone to commit this act. It can also be an intentional act or an \nunintentional act [5]. Academic institutions view plagiarism as a serious violation of academic \nintegrity  [6] since it diminishes a student\'s credibility for their academic work, and also detracts \nfrom a student\'s actual learning  or knowledge. To ensure fairness and uphold the integrity of  the academic process, many universities have implemented policies and support tools  [7] to \nhelp monitor the originality of all assignments, reports, and research projects.  \nUniversiti Tun Hussein Onn Malaysia (UTHM) allows a maximum limit of 30% \nsimilarity index or plagiarism index  [8]. All submitted academic work must not exceed this \nthreshold when excluding direct quotes, references, and standard templates. The 30% limit \nprovides a guideline for students to write their own content while allowing for some level of \nsimilarity that will occur naturally in all academic writing. Limiting similarity scores to less \nthan the percentage limit  will help ensure that what is submitted reflects the student’s own \nunderstanding of the material and is not just copied from a source or improperly reused . The \nUTHM policy promotes ethical writing practices, provides guidelines for academic honesty, \nand ensures students are assessed fairly based on their actual learning.  \n \n2.5 Method  or Technology  to Detect Plagiarism  \nThe plagiarism detection process is structured and equitable according to this workflow. In the \nfirst step, a lecturer sets up the assignment in the Learning Management System (LMS). After \nthat, the LMS will prepare the assignment for worry scanning automa tically. Next, all students\' \nassignments will be submitted to the LMS and time -stamped, but not compared yet; all \nassignments will be queued until after the submission deadline. After the due date has passed, \nthe LMS uses an automated process to compare ev ery submission to each other. This prevents \nstudents who submitted their assignments early from having an edge over their classmates and \nensures everyone receives equal treatment regarding plagiarism checking.  \n2.5.1 Cosine Similarity  \nCosine similarity  [9] is a method for identifying the degree to which two text documents match . \nA cosine similarity algorithm quantifies the degree of similarity between a document and \nanother document or group of documents by using numerical vector representations of the text \nand then calculating the cosine of the angle between the two vectors. A high cosine similarity \nscore indicates that the two documents share a great deal of commonality in terms of important \nwords, meaning their vectors are pointing toward the same direction. A significant advantage \nof cosine similarity is it only measures the relationship between the words in two different \ndocuments. For example, if the lengths of the two documents differ significantly, the cosine \nsimilarity algorithm will still produce an accurate comparison   2.5.2 Term Frequency –Inverse Document Frequency  \nThe statistical product term frequency -inverse document frequency (TF -IDF) is a means of \ndetermining the important words in text documents. TF -IDF does this by establishing the \nfrequency of occurrence of the word in the text document (TF), and then, the nu mber of \noccurrences of words considered generic or common amongst all submissions is reduced (IDF). \nUsing TF -IDF [10] when comparing student submissions assists in isolating and identifying \nunique or significant words, making it easier to find instances of potential and probable \nplagiarism. By isolating the highest contributing keywords to the originality of the submission s, \nTF-IDF contributes to increasing the likelihood that students\' submissions will be accurately \nevaluated.  \nExample:  \nTable 2 .1: TF -IDF \nWord  TF in Doc1  TF in Doc2  IDF TF-IDF (Doc1)  TF-IDF (Doc2)  \n\"algorithm\"  3 3 2 6 6 \n\"student\"  1 5 3 3 15 \nIf both have similar TF -IDF vectors , then the  documents are similar.  \n2.5.3 N -gram sequence matching  \nN-gram sequence matching  [11] is another means of determining similarity . N-grams are the \ncontinuous sub -sequences or called the chunks  of text of n terms that are each analysed for \nsimilarities. For instance, a 3 -word n -gram may include \"in this study\". In comparing all student \nsubmissions for similarities, the software will locate identical sequences across all student \nsubmissions. The more identical 3 -word n -gram sequences two students submit, the greater the \nsimilarity score assigned by the software. The power of N -gram matching to identify the \nsimilarities between submission s increases significantly when the N -grams are utilised when \nnoting similarities between assigned submissions because N -gram matching provides a \ncomparative analysis of sentence structure and order of phrases as opposed to just the \ncomparison of single ter m occurrences.  \n \n2.6 Study of Existing Related Systems   UTHM\'s LMS has proven to be an efficient platform for teaching and learning, allowing users \nto upload their content, submit assignments, take quizzes, and communicate with their lecturer . \nHowever, the AUTHOR LMS currently does not come equipped with a built -in plagiarism  \ndetection  tool, therefore, lecturers  use a third -party service  such as Turnitin [12] to check the \noriginality of their students\' work. The use of an external service for checking the originality \nof student works can be inconsistent and time -consuming . \nSimilar to the AUTHOR LMS, other currently utilized LMS\'s such as Google \nClassroom and Edmodo also do not have built -in anti -plagiarism tools. Google Classroom has \nan extremely high level of accessibility, ease of use, and provides easy access to all of th e \ndifferent tools available through Google Workspace  [13]. However, Google Classroom relies \non third -party companies for their plagiarism detection tools and typically those companies \ncharge high subscription fees. Edmodo, on the other hand, provides an excellent way to \nencourage interaction and collaboration, but does not offer an automated plagiarism detection \nsystem. Therefore, lecturers are required to manually check student work for originality which \nmay or may not be reliable.  \n2.6.1 AUTHOR UTHM  \nUTHM\'s official Learning Management System (LMS), AUTHOR, offers the necessary \nfunctionality which is uploading educational content, submitting assessments, providing an \nevaluation system, grading students to create a structured digital learning space. Unfortunately, \nAUTHOR does not have integrated tools for detecting plagiarism; therefore, lecturer s must use \nexternal systems like Turnitin or other online tools. With the proposed solution, similarity \nscanning, text comparison algorithms, and automated repor ts would be added to the submission \nworkflow so that an instantaneous analysis is available for the lecturer  at the time of \nsubmission. The systemic inclusion of the similarity check as part of the standard assessment \nprocess and leveraging AUTHOR\'s existing submission framework allows for a more \nconsistent evaluation of student work while improving academic int egrity. The proposed \nsystem provides an efficient, scalable means to reinforce the fairness and reliability of the \nevaluation of student work.  \n \n \n   \nFigure 2.1 : AUTHOR Dashboard  \n \n2.6.2 Google Classroom  \nGoogle Classroom [14] is a great online educational management system for how it makes \ndistributing assignments, communicating with students or staff, grading students, and \norganizing classes. However, Google’s current plagiarism detection features are limited to paid \noptions that require additional tools. The proposed system will have similarities to the existing \nGoogle Classroom in that it will have some or all of the same features to allow for assignment \nsubmissions and lecturer  reviews. But the proposed system will have the  added benefit of \nautomatic similarity checking, detailed originality reports with highlighted matched text, and a \nbreakdown of the similarities produced from checked documents. The proposed system will \nallow for a central location to save student submissi ons, which will allow for comparisons \nbetween students and across groups of students. This capability will provide an advantage with \nrespect to internal plagiarism detection capabilities; therefore, the proposed system will expand \non Google Classroom’s str engths by providing a more comprehensive, scalable, and tailored \napproach to plagiarism detection based on UTHM’s needs.  \n \n \n \n  \nFigure 2.2: Google Classroom Dashboard  \n2.6.3 Edmodo  \nThe educational platform Edmodo [15] provides communication, engagement, resource -\nsharing, and other benefits to educators and learners through a social -media -style website, yet \nthe application of Edmodo for higher learning is limited because Edmodo does not contain \nintegrated tools for deter mining instances of plagiarism. However, Edmodo can still serve as a \nsource of inspiration for the development of the new plagiarism detection system’s user -\nfriendly dashboards, reports, and notifications. In conclusion, Edmodo is a very effective \nmeans of  managing a classroom environment and facilitating communication between lecturers  \nand students; however, it cannot provide universities with the necessary institutional -level \nanalysis of originality of submitted work in support of academic integrity, as will be provided \nin the proposed system through centralised management of the submission of work . \n \n \n \n \n \n \n  \nFigure 2. 3: Edmodo Dashboard  \n2.7 Comparison with Existing System  \nThis chapter compares the proposed system  to three well -known Learning Management \nSystems. The LMS\'s compared are A UTH OR, Google Classroom, and Edmodo. Although \nthese systems provide features which promote online learning, each has a level of depth, \nconfigurability, and applicability to the customization of an institution. This comparison \ndemonstrates the advantages and dis advantages of each existing LMS; therefore, the research \nof this chapter provides an evaluation, based on specific criteria for each LMS, including user \nauthentication, document processing, communication tools, assessment capabilities, analytics, \nand secur ity of the system. Additionally, the research illustrates how the proposed system  \nintegrates and improves many key elements to address the operational requirements and \nobjectives of an academic environment.  \nTable 2. 2: Comparison Table  \nFeatures / \nSystem  AUTHOR  Google \nClassroom  Edmodo  Proposed \nSystem  \nLogin  ✓ ✓ ✓ ✓ \nUser Role \nManagement  ✓  ✓  ✓  ✓ \nUpload / Submit \nDocuments  ✓ ✓ ✓ ✓ \n Communication \n/ Announcements  ✓  ✓  ✓  ✓ \nAssessment / \nTracking \nProgress  ✓  ✓  ✓  ✓ \nReport & \nAnalytics  ✓  Limited  Limited  ✓  \nFile Sharing  ✓ ✓ ✓ ✓ \nFeedback \nSystem  ✓  ✓  ✓  ✓ \nData Backup  X  ✓  ✓  ✓  \nSecurity / Access \nControl  ✓ ✓  ✓  ✓  \nBuilt -in \nPlagiarism \nDetector  X X X ✓ \nIn conclusion, the comparison shows that while AUTHOR, Google Classroom and Edmodo \nprovide useful resources for learning purposes, there are many differences between the three \nplatforms regarding security and academic integrity features. For example, on on e hand, \nAUTHOR has an Education -provided, secure, university -managed environment . From another \nperspective, Google Classroom also provides strong data protection through Google\'s cloud \nstorage . In contrast, Edmodo provides more communication and engagement  capabilities than \nit does security  compliance capabilities. For instance, Edmodo provides only basic security \ncontrols and does not provide any type of similarity analysis for submissions uploaded by \nstudents.  However, all three LMSs do not provide built -in plagiarism tool.  Contrarily, with the \nproposed system, it improves security and enhances the way that student submissions will be \nprocessed through the integration of an automated plagiarism detection module into the student \nupload process. Every assign ment that is uploaded will now be scanned, analysed, and securely \nstored, significantly decreasing the likelihood of academic fraud . As a result, the proposed \nsystem creates a medium to ensure consistency and reliability in the area of academic integrity.   2.8 Chapter Summary  \nThis chapter thoroughly reviewed related literature concerning assessment techniques; the role \nof Learning Management Systems (LMS) in education; the issue of plagiarism; and existing \nonline tools for plagiarism detection, as a reference for creating the Plagiarism Detect or in \nLearning Management System . A comparison of currently available platforms (AUTHOR, \nGoogle Classroom and Edmodo) revealed that these three platforms support the teaching and \nlearning processes, but none provide necessary integrated or automated ways to detect \nsimilarities and plagiarism at the level of universities. Therefore, these findings supported the \nproposal of a complete integrated solution. Finally, this chapter discussed how the proposed \nsystem  uses algorithms such as TF -IDF, cosine similarity and n -gram analysis to achieve \nautomated scanning for similarities, comprehensive originality reports, comparisons between \ntwo or more bodies of work, organizational/comparative repositories, and analytica l data on \nwriters. In conclusion, this chapter showed how current systems are not sufficient to enable the \nenforcement of academic integrity in relation to plagiarism and illustrated how the proposed \nsystem  provides a comprehensive, institution -oriented approach to supporting UTHM’s \nacademic integrity objectives.  \n \nReferences  \n[1] Pusat Teknologi Maklumat, “AUTHOR UTHM,” UTHM Publisher. [Online]. Available: \nauthor.uthm.edu.my  \n[2] I. Maslov, S. Nikou, and P. Hansen, “Exploring user experience of learning management \nsystem,” International Journal of Information and Learning Technology , vol. 38, no. 4, \n2021, doi: 10.1108/IJILT -03-2021 -0046.  \n[3] D. Turnbull, R. Chugh, and J. Luck, “An Overview of the Common Elements of \nLearning Management System Policies in Higher Education Institutions,” TechTrends , \npp. 855 –867, 2022, doi: 10.1007/s11528 -022-00752 -7. \n[4] M. Furqon, P. Sinaga, L. Liliasari, and L. S. Riza, “The Impact of Learning Management \nSystem (LMS) Usage on Students,” TEM Journal , vol. 12, no. 2, pp. 1082 –1089, 2023, \ndoi: 10.18421/TEM122 -54. \n[5] Maimunah et al. , “Cutting the prevalence of plagiarism in the digital era: Student \nteachers’ perceptions on plagiarism in Indonesian Higher Education,” Problems of \nEducation in the 21st Century , vol. 76, no. 5, pp. 663 –677, 2018, doi: \n10.33225/pec/18.76.663.   [6] C. Bouaine, F. Benabbou, and I. Sadgali, “Word Embedding for High Performance \nCross -Language Plagiarism Detection Techniques,” International Journal of Interactive \nMobile Technologies , vol. 17, no. 10, pp. 69 –91, 2023, doi: 10.3991/ijim.v17i10.38891.  \n[7] V . Cebrián -Robles, F. J. Ruíz -Rey, M. Raposo -Rivas, and M. Cebrián -de-la-Serna, \n“Impact of Digital Contexts in the Training of University Education Students,” Educ Sci \n(Basel) , vol. 13, no. 9, 2023, doi: 10.3390/educsci13090923.  \n[8] M. O. Eze and S. A. Kamboh, “Plagiarism Index Estimation Algorithm: A Quantitative \nApproach,” Int J Comput Appl , vol. 111, no. 17, pp. 36 –46, 2015, doi: 10.5120/ijais15 -\n451307.  \n[9] R. Fauzi, M. Iqbal, and T. Haryanti, “Design and Implementation of a Final Project \nPlagiarism Detection System Using Cosine Similarity Method,” IJAIT (International \nJournal of Applied Information Technology) , vol. 05, no. 02, p. 1, 2022, doi: \n10.25124/ijait.v5i02.4146.  \n[10] S. Qaiser and R. Ali, “Text Mining: Use of TF -IDF to Examine the Relevance of Words \nto Documents,” Int J Comput Appl , vol. 181, no. 1, pp. 25 –29, 2018, doi: \n10.5120/ijca2018917395.  \n[11] M. Davoodifard, “Automatic Detection of Plagiarism in Writing,” Studies in Applied \nLinguistics and TESOL , vol. 21, no. 2, pp. 54 –60, 2022, doi: 10.52214/salt.v21i2.9058.  \n[12] L. Graham -Matheson and S. Starr, “Is it cheating or learning the craft of writing? Using \nTurnitin to help students avoid plagiarism,” Research in Learning Technology , vol. 21, \nno. 1063519, pp. 1 –13, 2013, doi: 10.3402/rlt.v21i0.17218.  \n[13] U. Akcil, H. Uzunboylu, and E. Kinik, “Integration of technology to learning -teaching \nprocesses and google workspace tools: A literature review,” Sustainability (Switzerland) , \nvol. 13, no. 9, 2021, doi: 10.3390/su13095018.  \n[14] Google, “Google Classroom,” Google for Education. [Online]. Available: \nclassroom.google.com  \n[15] N. Borg, “Edmodo,” Edmodo, Inc. [Online]. Available: edmodo.com  \n  \n \n ', 8.20);
INSERT INTO `submissions` (`submission_id`, `student_username`, `course_id`, `file_name`, `submitted_on`, `submitted_at`, `activity_id`, `extracted_text`, `plagiarism_score`) VALUES
(23, 'stud3', 5, 'stud3_11_1776707465963_chap3_psm_after_correct2.pdf', '2026-04-21 01:51:06', '2026-04-21 01:51:06', 11, ' \n    \n              \n        \n    \n    \n \nA Plagiarism Detector in Learning Management  \nSystem for UTHM  \n       \n       \n       \n       \n       \nNAMA       \nName       :   DIV AKHAR A/L RAJAH       \nNO. MATRIK      \nMatric No.       :   AI230082      \nTARIKH       \nDate       :   4/12/2025       \nSUPERVISOR       :   Dr. Nur Ziadah Binti Harun       \n     \n                                                          \n    \n   \n \n    \n \n  \n \n \nCHAP TER THREE  \n \nMETHODOLOGY  \nThis chapter explain the use of prototype model in this project and the activities that \nhad been carried out in each phase.  Section  3.1 shows that  this project will use an Agile \nModel Methodology for System Development . The Agile Model Methodology creates \nthe entire system with multiple cycles. The Agile Model Methodology allows each \nmodel to be enhanced through constant feedback from lecturers  and students. Section \n3.2 showed  a highly structured development workflow  is used , with 5 distinct phases , \nPlanning, Analysis, Design, Implementations, Testing,  and specific activities and \ndeliverables to create a user-friendly solutio n. Section 3. 3 shared about the \nmethodology for designing a plagiarism detection system for UTHM, which takes  an \niterative Agile approach . This means  that the design is  based on student  and lecturer \nfeedback  and allows for improvement at all stages of development . Each phase of \ndevelopment is outlined . These phases enable  the creation of a working  prototype  that \nis easy for users to operate and meets  the requirements  of academic Integrity . \n3.1 Agile Model  \nThe Agile Model is an iterative development process that creates prototype system \nversions that can be further enhanced through multiple iterations [1] Continuous \ndelivery of user feedback helps to implement ongoing improvements to each new \nversion of the prototype. The Agile approach emphasizes user satisfaction, \ncollaborative processes, and flexibility in producing a final product that continues to \nimpr ove over time by using the multiple refinements from iterations throughout the \nentire life cycle of the product. The Agile Model contains the following phases , \nPlanning,  Analysis, Design, Implementation , Testing, Maintena nce. Each phase is \ndeveloped from the last, and iterations are utilized between phases to allow for \ncontinuous sharing between phases until the prototypes develop into the final system.    \nDiagram 3.1: Agile Model Phases  \n3.1.1 Planning Phase  \nDuring the planning phase of the project, the information w as gathered on the project \ngoals, objectives, and requirements through discussions with stakeholders including , \nlecturers , students,  and UTHM IT portal team  (Pusat Teknologi Maklumat UTHM) . \nThe planning phase defines the requirements for the plagiarism detection modul e. For \nexample , the ability to upload documents, check for similarities, manage users, and \ncreate reports. The project scope, project constraints, timeline and technologies \nrequired for  the project are also established. The planning phase creates user stories or \nfeature lists to represent what the system will be like from a user\'s perspective. User  \nstories and lists will form the basis of future development cycles. The planning phase \nwill help ensure that the development process is  understand able on  what will need to \nbe developed prior to moving on.  \n3.1.2 Analysis Phase  \nTo successfully design and develop a plagiarism detection  in a Learning Management \nSystem , it is important to first conduct an analysis phase of each functional and \ntechnical requirement. The Analysis phase is necessary to determine the functional and \ntechnical requirements for a plagiarism detection module, and to prepare the system to \nAGILE  \nMODEL  AGILE  \nMODEL   meet the specific needs of its users, including students and lecturers. The analysis \nphase identifies student needs, including the ability for students to upload assignments \nwith ease and receive notifications when their assignment has been submitted. Lecturer \nneeds include automated similarity verification, detailed similarity rep orts, and ease of \naccess to student documents. The analysis phase also determines the types of \nalgorithms that will be used to process, compare, and validate submitted documents \nand defines how submitted documents will be processed, stored, and compared.  \nThe analysis of the current challenges faced by the AUTHOR as well as the \nlack of an integrated plagiarism detection system will provide the necessary data to \ndesign a new system to meet these needs and specifications. The Analysis phase will \nalso include all technical limitations related to the implementation of a plagiarism \ndetection module, such as the accuracy of algorithms, server loads and response times, \nin order to develop a complete system that meets all technical requirements. In \naddition, at the end of the analysis phase a detailed list of system requirements and \nworkflow behaviour for the proposed plagiarism detection module will be available, \nwhich will assist in the design and development of the plagiarism detection module.  \n3.1.3 Design Phase  \nAll components of the system will be organised as part of creating a system design that \nensures proper functionality, and ease of use for both lecturers and students. In order \nto achieve this goal, it was essential to define key elements of the system, def ine how \nthe plagiarism detection module interacts with the submission process, and provide the \nuser interface layout so that the user interface feels easy to use. Additionally, it was \nnecessary to determine how the system will perform other essential funct ions, such as \nfile upload capabilities, generating and providing similarity reports, and sending \nalerts/notifications to users. The database structure will also be developed over time \nusing Entity -Relationship Diagrams (ERD) and Data Flow Diagram (DFD).  T he \ndevelopment of user interface layouts using Figma will provide clear visualisation and \ninteraction opportunities prior to the beginning of development, as well as allow for \nease of collaboration and adaptability based on feedback from both lecturers and  \nstudents [2] . \n \n  3.1.4 Implementation Phase  \nThe Agile development of the system is in phases with an iterative approach following \na sprint model to break down each of the functions into smaller segments. The four \nmajor incremental system functions are user login, document upload, similarity \ncomparis on, and report creation. Each segment will be constructed, tested, and \nenhanced during its respective sprint until it has reached its final state for production \nuse. Plagiarism detection algorithms will also undergo the same process and be \nintegrated into the workflow for automatic evaluation of all documents uploaded.  \nBackend functionality will be programmed in PHP and Python, and the \nunderlying data will be stored in a MySQL database. Frontend functionality will be \ndeveloped in HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. At the end of each module, stakeholders \nwill be able to see how t he module operates and provide feedback. Recommended \nchanges will be made before progress continues on the next sprint.  \n3.1.5 Testing Phase  \nThe testing process is designed to verify that the system performs in accordance with \nthe requirements specified and that it works correctly and efficiently. The first stage of \ntesting is Unit Testing. During this stage each Module (e.g., File Uploading, Similarity \nCheck Calculation, Report Generation) is t ested separately to verify it is functioning \nas expected. The next stage of testing is System Integration Testing. During System \nIntegration Testing, modules are tested together as a complete system and t he flow of \ndata between Modules is verified as being error -free. The final stage of testing is User \nAcceptance Testing (UAT). During UAT, Lecturers and Students test the system to \nassure themselves that it is easy to use, performs as intended, and satisfies th e needs \nof its users. Each of the above tests contributes to creating a reliable, usable, and \ndeployable system  [3]. \n3.1.6 Maintenance Phase  \nDuring the Maintenance Phase, the plagiarism detection tool is also supported via the \ncontinuation of development. This includes fixing any bugs that have been reported by \nusers as well as enhancing detection of plagiarism through updates to the existing \nalgorithms and enhancing overall performance. New functio nalities, interface \nimprovements, or security enhancements based on feedback from lecturers and  students to the Plagiarism Detection Tool will be implemented during the maintenance \nphase. Improvements to maintain an acceptable level of compliance to academic \nstandards will also be included.  \n3.2 System Development Workflow  \nThere are a total of six phases from the prototype model. As shown in Table 3.1, each \nphase has its assignment and output that needs to be produced during the entire project \ndevelopment.  \nTable 3.1: Software development activities and their task  \nPhase  Tasks  Outputs  \nPlanning  • Define project objectives and \nscope  \n• Identify users (lecturer & \nstudent)  \n• Determine features and \nconstraints  \n• Develop project timeline and \nresource plan  • Project scope definition  \n• Preliminary timeline  \n \nAnalysis  • Gather system requirements \nfrom lecturer and students  \n• Identify functional and non -\nfunctional requirements  \n• Prepare use -case descriptions \nand workflow scenarios  • Software Requirements \nSpecification (SRS)  \n• List of system \nrequirements  \n• Develop Gantt chart   \n \nDesign  • Develop system architecture and \nworkflow  \n• Design user interface layout and \nmockups  • UI mockups/layouts  \n• System architecture design  \n• Database schema and DFD   • Plan database schema and data \nrelationships  • Entity Relationship \nDiagram  \nImplementation  • Develop UI using chosen \ntechnology  \n• Code system modules \n(submission, evaluation, \nfeedback, etc.)  \n• Integrate front -end and database  \n• Conduct internal debugging  • Working prototype  \n•Functional module \nintegration  \n• Source code files  \nTesting  • Conduct functional testing of \neach feature  \n• Perform user acceptance testing \nwith lecturer and students  \n• Identify and log bugs/issues  • Test case results  \n• UAT feedback forms  \n• List of bugs and \nimprovement items  \nMaintenance  • Collect detailed feedback from \nlecturers and students  \n• Review issues, usability \nconcerns, missing requirements  \n• Refine and update prototype \nbased on findings  \n• Retest after modifications  • Improvement summary  \n• Updated prototype version  \n• Validation report after \niteration  \n \n \n \n \n \n  3.3 Chapter Summary  \nThe methodology used to design the prototype plagiarism detection system for UTHM \nis detailed in this chapter . This chapter introduces the iterative approach selected \nbecause it enables ongoing improvements based on input from both lecturers  and \nstudents. Each phase of development is outlined, beginning with the planning phase \nwhere objectives and scope are established, then moving on to analysing the functional \nrequirements and user requirements. The design phase provides an overview of the \nsystem architec ture, interface design, and database schema that were all converted into \na live prototype during implementation. Once the prototype was developed, testing \nwas performed to ensure functionality and usability of the system and any problems \nfound were address ed through the structured test and review cycle outlined in the \nmethodology. This methodology allowed for the creation of a practical and user -\nfriendly system that effectively meets the goals of Academic Integrity.  \n \nReferences  \n[1] Tutorialspoint, “Sdlc - Agile Model,” SDLC - Agile Model , pp. 1–2, 2015, \n[Online]. Available: \nhttps://www.tutorialspoint.com/sdlc/sdlc_agile_model.htm  \n[2] M. F. Santoso, “Implementation Of UI/UX Concepts And Techniques In \nWeb Layout Design With Figma,” Jurnal Teknologi Dan Sistem Informasi \nBisnis, vol. 6, no. 2, pp. 279 –285, 2024, doi: 10.47233/jteksis.v6i2.1223.  \n[3] S. Kulkarni, “The Necessity of System Integration Testing (SIT) and User \nAcceptance Testing (UAT) in Project Lifecycle,” Interantional Journal of \nScientific Research in Engineering and Management , vol. 08, no. 11, pp. \n1–7, 2024, doi: 10.55041/ijsrem7673.  \n  ', 4.20),
